// runtime_struct_reassign_single — regression for the struct-local
// REASSIGNMENT codegen bug (t113 false-negative: a prior agent concluded the
// crash did not exist; it segfaulted 20/20).
//
// Trigger: an AssignExpr whose target is a struct-typed local (`s`) and whose
// value is a struct-returning call (`mk()`). The generic CallExpr eval() path
// has no Win64 hidden-return-pointer ABI, so `mk()` was called with rcx unset
// (the hidden pointer) -> it wrote its 8-byte result to an unmapped address ->
// segfault 139, 20/20 (both `ember run` and `ember bench`). The `let s = mk()`
// INITIALIZATION path worked (LetStmt uses eval_struct_returning_call with
// rax=&local); only the `s = mk()` REASSIGNMENT path was broken.
//
// Fix (src/codegen.cpp AssignExpr eval case): detect a struct-returning
// CallExpr assigned to a struct-typed local/global, LEA the target's address
// into rax as the hidden word-0 pointer, and call eval_struct_returning_call
// (mirroring the LetStmt-init path) instead of generic eval() + store_rax.
//
// Expected rc: 42 (s.v after `s = mk()` where mk returns S{v:42}). Kept < 256
// so the lang runner's 8-bit exit-code reading is exact.
struct S { v: i64; }
fn mk() -> S { return S { v: 42 }; }
fn main() -> i64 {
    let mut s: S = S { v: 0 };
    s = mk();
    return s.v;
}
